<DOC><DOCNO> AP880914-0137 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1422EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a PM-VirginiaHostages 5thLd-Writethru a0700 09-14 0306</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Virginia Hostages, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0700,0309</SECOND><HEAD>URGENT</HEAD><HEAD>Hostages Taken At Recruiting Station</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS typo in lead to make quote read `peace in Lebanon.;COMBINES pvs urgent series.</NOTE><BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A gunman took 11 hostages at a militaryrecruiting station today but freed them unharmed hours later aftertwo radio stations agreed to air a statement asserting his goal was``peace in Lebanon.''   He surrendered moments later, shortly before 2 p.m. No one wasinjured.   The unidentified gunman, who had described himself as ``a localperson of Lebanese descent,'' was armed with an AK-47, an automaticrifle that is standard issue in Communist countries, said policeLt. C.M. Schesventer.   Police negotiated by telephone with the man, who had claimed twoarmed companions, but police learned from freed captives there wasonly one gunman.   The 11 captives _ nine military personnel and two civilians _included a high school senior enlisting in the service, saidSchesventer.   Hostages began coming out, alone and in twos, about every 10minutes shortly after radio stations WRNL-AM and WRXL-FM twiceaired a message at the gunman's demand around noon, said MarianneJennings, news director at the stations.   ``There is a hostage situation at Tuckernuck Square ShoppingCenter,'' the statement read. ``There have been no injuries.Negotiations are proceeding. The hostage-takers have so far beencooperative. They're holding an undetermined number of people. Thehostage-takers' goal is peace in Lebanon.''   The U.S. Armed Forces Recruiting Center is in a shopping centerthat includes 30 stores. All were evacuated.   Local and state police carrying automatic weapons ringed thearea. The shopping center is in a heavily developed commercialstrip.   Sands said police received a call at 9:15 a.m. about ahostage-taking at the recruiting center, which housesrepresentatives of several military branches.</TEXT></DOC>